    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-09T07:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-09T07:30:00-05:00" n="485"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d485">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander of the United States Yangtze Patrol</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marquart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="35" xml:id="d485fn35">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Navy Department.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-09T20:30:00+08:00"
                            >December 9, 1937—8:30 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 9—7:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0009. Nanking city gates closed, many fires burning both sides of river,
                    waterfront area outside city walls practically deserted, intensive bombing by
                    Japanese through day. <hi rend="italic">Panay</hi> moved 2 miles up river from
                    present anchorage to facilitate evacuation remaining nationals. U. S. S. <hi
                        rend="italic">Guam</hi> standing by Wuhu where 16 United States nationals
                    remain.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
